TY  - JOUR
T1  - A New Approach to Stockout Penalties
AU  - Schwartz, Benjamin L.
Y1  - 1966/08/01
PY  - 1966
DA  - 1966/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.12.12.B538
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.12.12.B538
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-538
EP  - B-544
VL  - 12
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Classical inventory theory considers that stockouts generate penalty costs to the firm, often assumed to be proportional to the excess of demand over supply. While such a concept is sometimes appropriate, it does not correctly reflect the effect of loss of goodwill. The latter is characterized by the fact that a disappointed customer reacts in the future to change his purchasing habits. Thus the nature of the effect is that subsequent demand is perturbed, a phenomenon quite different from having an immediate penalty cost imposed. Models with this property are termed perturbed demand, abbreviated PD. In this paper, this concept is defined precisely, and some of its properties are developed. Some typical cases are solved to determine optimal policies when PD prevails.
AB  - Classical inventory theory considers that stockouts generate penalty costs to the firm, often assumed to be proportional to the excess of demand over supply. While such a concept is sometimes appropriate, it does not correctly reflect the effect of loss of goodwill. The latter is characterized by the fact that a disappointed customer reacts in the future to change his purchasing habits. Thus the nature of the effect is that subsequent demand is perturbed, a phenomenon quite different from having an immediate penalty cost imposed. Models with this property are termed perturbed demand, abbreviated PD. In this paper, this concept is defined precisely, and some of its properties are developed. Some typical cases are solved to determine optimal policies when PD prevails.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.12.12.B538
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.12.12.B538
Y2  - 2024/03/27
